I strongly recommend, as a matter of style, to use curly braces every time they are syntactically allowed.  It will prevent bugs like the one you have here.  First, let me write the equivalent code to yours **with** braces:

        for (int n = 1; n &lt; x.length()-1; n++) {
            c = x.charAt(n);
        }
        if (!Character.isLetterOrDigit(c)) {
            eventText = eventText + event.getText();
        }
        countNonAlpha ++;

If it&#39;s not obvious to you why this is equivalent to what you wrote, bear in mind that, when there are no curly braces following a `for` or `if` statement, **only the next single statement is executed as part of its block**.  The indentation of subsequent lines doesn&#39;t matter at all (like it does in python).

If you write what you&#39;re intending to execute with curly braces (as is generally strongly recommended by nearly everyone):

        for (int n = 1; n &lt; x.length()-1; n++) {
            c = x.charAt(n);
            if (!Character.isLetterOrDigit(c)) {
                eventText = eventText + event.getText();
                countNonAlpha ++;
            }
        }

Again, always use curly braces, unless you have a clear understanding of when it&#39;s typically OK (for example, everything on one line).  But even when you think it&#39;s OK, it&#39;s still probably more clear to use curly braces on separate lines.

